/i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Foljambe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: nickname from Old French  <i>fol</i> ‘foolish, silly’ +  <i>jambe</i> ‘leg’, probably a nickname for a lame person, someone with a maimed or crooked leg;  compare  Belgian  . In Old French  <i>fol</i> could be used of something useless or of little value, e.g.  <i>farine folle</i> ‘mill dust’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fulljames","meanings":["English: variant of   Foljambe   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Belgian","meanings":["Norman, English, Scottish: nickname from Anglo-Norman French  <i>bele jambe</i> ‘fine leg’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":8,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":33,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Foljambe was born in 1282, in 